data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Inventory of Issues

| API | Line | Problem on .NET 8 |
|-----|------|--------------------|
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `Stop()` | Obsolete (`SYSLIB0046` in .NET 9); unreliable for waking `WaitOne` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — **hard crash** |
| `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` | `RunLoop()` | Not cancellation-aware; can't be woken cooperatively |

**Patterns identified:**
1. **Cancellable work loop** — `while (true)` in `RunLoop`
2. **Blocking call interruption** — `WaitOne()` needs to wake on cancellation

**Bonus bug in original:** Multiple rapid `Enqueue` calls can race — `Set()` coalesces signals but only one `Dequeue` runs per wake, losing items.

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEventSlim _newEvent = new();
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var token = _cts.Token;
        try
        {
            while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Blocks until signaled OR cancelled — replaces bare WaitOne()
                _newEvent.Wait(token);
                _newEvent.Reset();

                // Drain all queued items (fixes the lost-signal bug)
                while (true)
                {
                    string? item;
                    lock (_lock)
                    {
                        if (_queue.Count == 0) break;
                        item = _queue.Dequeue();
                    }
                    Handle(item);
                }
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException)
        {
            // Expected on shutdown — exit cleanly
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        // Cooperative cancellation replaces Interrupt + Abort
        _cts.Cancel();
        _thread?.Join(5000);
        // No fallback Abort needed — the loop checks the token
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

## Key Changes Explained

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `ManualResetEvent` | `ManualResetEventSlim` | Lighter; its `Wait(CancellationToken)` overload enables cooperative wake-up |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | `_newEvent.Wait(token)` | Throws `OperationCanceledException` when token fires — thread wakes immediately |
| `while (true)` | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` | Loop checks cancellation cooperatively each iteration |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | `_cts.Cancel()` | Signals the token, which unblocks `Wait(token)` |
| `Thread.Abort()` | *(removed)* | Not available in .NET 8; cooperative cancellation makes it unnecessary |
| Single `Dequeue` per wake | Drain loop | Fixes race where multiple `Set()` calls coalesce into one wake |

## Pitfalls to Watch For

1. **`Thread.Abort` is a hard crash**, not a warning — it throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` at runtime on .NET 8. This is the #1 priority to fix.
2. **Don't forget `Dispose`** — `CancellationTokenSource` leaks timer/callback resources if not disposed.
3. **Cancellation is cooperative** — if `Handle(item)` does long-running work, it should also accept and check the `CancellationToken` or cancellation will be delayed until the next loop iteration.
4. **`ManualResetEventSlim.Wait(token)`** throws `OperationCanceledException` — catch it at the loop boundary, not inside per-item logic.
